ate how Meg uses grammar and narrative structure to create and recreate emotional experiences that maintain her agoraphobic identity. In this work Capps and Ochs propose a startling new view of agoraphobia as a communicative disorder. Constructing Panic opens up the largely overlooked potential for linguistic and narrative analysis by revealing the roots of panic and by offering a unique framework for therapeutic intervention. Readers will find in these pages hope for managing panic through careful attention to how we tell the story of our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAgoraphobiaxCase studies. 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aPanic attacks. 0aPersonal construct theory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychopathology / Anxieties & Phobias.2bisacsh1 aBruner, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOchs, Elinor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674029187zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029187423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674029187/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK